Ageing meets kidney disease.
Chronic kidney disease (CKD) is defined as abnormalities of kidney structure or function, present for 3 months, with implications for health. The most used diagnostic criteria are a urinary albumin: creatinine ratio =30 mg/g or an estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) provides an overview of key topics, including cognitive decline, sarcopaenia, wasting and cardiovascular and non-cardiovascular morbidity and mortality, the management of kidney failure and gender differences in CKD progression.
